solution.p:
For continuity on (-1,1), let a\in (-1,1) be arbitrary.  For continuity, we need to show that \ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a).  Then,
	\ds \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = 3+\sqrt{1-a^2} 
Since f(a) = 3+\sqrt{1-a^2}, the function is continuous on (-1,1), and thus continuous on the interval [-1,1].

example.statement:
Find the interval(s) on which the following functions are continuous



		f(x) = x^{67}-47.521x^{51}+719




		g(x) = \dfrac{x^2+2x+17}{x^2-1}




		h(x) = \sqrt{x} + \dfrac{x+1}{x-1} + \dfrac{x+1}{x^2+1}




		\cos\lrpar{\dfrac{1}{x}}

